column2: The temperature is 90 degrees- NW wind- and algae floating.
The temperature is 85 degrees- south wind or breeze- and algae floating.
South wind- cloudy- the temperature is 88 degrees- windy- and the water is greenish brown.
Lake is to low to get boat out to get a secchi disc reading.
Fine (0.5-2.0) algae particles (green) prevalent- forming rivulets at surface.  No odors.
Fine (0.5-1.0mm) algae particles (green) prevalent- but no rivulets at surface. no odors.
Particulates 0.1-2 mm- fluffy and whitish to eye. (tss equiv. approximately 10 ppm) .  Waves 0.5-1 Ft high.
Quite windy- waves 1-1.5 feet- anchor could not hold over deep hole.  Lots of particles- wide size range.
Particulate size range narrow (1-2 mm).  Chlorophyll filtrate volume much lower than expected.
Particulate size range wide (0-5 mm).  Surface algae rivulets visible- although wind is nearly calm.
Algae particles 0.5-2 mm- TSS equiv. @ surface is 35-40 mg/l- at 3 feet 5-10 mg/l- and filtered volume is 1500 ml.
Algae 0.1-2 mm- TSS equiv. @ surface 15-20 mg/l- @ 3 feet 5-10 mg/l- and filtered volume is 1250 ml.
Algae 0.5-1 mm- TSS equiv. @ surface 20-30 mg/l @ 3 feet 10-15 mg/l- and filtered volume is 358 ml.
Algae 0.5-2mm.  TSS equiv. @ surface 30-40 mg/l.  Filtered Volume 900 ML.
Algae virtually gone- TSS equiv.  less than  10 mg/l- filtered volume is 600 ml- and very windy.
Particulates: brown- 0.1-0.2 mm. TSS equiv. @ surface= 5-10 mg/L- ~5mg @ 3 feet.
Lots of weed shards. Lots of darters (1 mm -3-4 mm L) Dead snails frequent.
99% of algae  less than = 1 mm; 1%  greater than = 1-2 mm (green). No darters. Sheared weeds- dead snails occasional.
Pea soup algae. Est TSS @ 100-200 mg/L at surface. Bulrush shards frequent. Many dead snails.
Still green with algae! Est TSS @ surface = 25-30 mg/L; at 3 ft = 10-15 mg/L. No weed shards or dead snails.
Many very small- colorless mostly- rest brownish particles suggested spring debris- not growth.
Air smells clean out here- not so at shore.  Lots of whitish floc 1-4 mm. Filter pad tinted green with 3 green spots 1-1.5 mm.
Whitish floc seen in June is gone.  Water still turbid.  Filter tinted green- but less so than in June.
Floc particle size unusually uniform and  less than = 0.5 mm. Filter tinted brown this time.  Wind exceeded 20-25 mph on 8/23.
Very few particles observed.  Clarity judged as "clear".
TSS equivalent 10-15 mg/l.  Algae noted on fiter disk.  35 ft D.O.: between 0.5-7.6 mg/l. Probe touching the upper edge of muck at the bottom.
Algae particles about same as in previous month.  Air temp. 91 F.  Little wind.
Algae particles present.  Most  less than 0.5 mm- rest 1-2 mm.  Est. TSS 30-10 mg/l.  D.O. at 38 ft. between 0.1-2.3 mg/l.  Probe touching the upper edge of muck at bottom.
Est. TSS equivalent 5-10 mg/l.  None settle out.  Less algae color on filter disk.  Clarity very good.
Many daphnia (~50/l).  Residue on filter was brownish-green.
Daphnia present (~10/l).  Much more algae than in July.  Very windy.  TSS est'd 5-10 mg/l.
Cloudless sky; est TSS ~ 10 mg/l (Excellent).  Daphnia present (~ 10/l).  A little algae present.
No moving organisms.  TSS estimate  under 2 mg/l (clear).  Highest Secchi reading for May (ever )
1 daphnia / 8 oz = 4/L.  TSS estimate less than 5 mg/l (clear).
Daphnia - 24/L.  TSS estimate 10-15 mg/L.  Lots of weed shards floating.
Daphnia = 32/L.  TSS estimate 10 mg/L.  No algal bloom this summer.
No moving organisms.  Clearest water seen since October 1999! (Zebra mussels impact).
No daphnia.  TSS est'd less than or equal to 5 mg/l in sample from column sampler (quite clear).
8 daphnia/L.  Lots of weed shards related to motorboat activity.
Est. TSS at surface 15-20 mg/l vs. 5-10 mg/l in lab sample.  F. pad definitely green.
Daphnia count 2/L.  Algal bloom in force.
Daphnia count highest ever (16-25/L).  Residue on 0.5 pad was uniformly brown with spots of algae.
Water looks nice- but no Daphnia. Wind ~ 5 mph. Halo around sun in haze.
TSS estimate 5-15 mg/L. No Daphnia. 3-4 fuzzballs (8 oz.- 1-1.5 mm)- algae

column1: Wind - calm. Neglected to assess for Daphnia.

column2: No Daphnia observed in 200 ml sample. Secchi reading the best of the season.
Lots of finely chopped weed particles at the surface of the water. Less so at deep hole. Estimated TSS @ 2-5 mg/l.
Clarity very good- but waves were 15-20 inches high. 2 Daphnia per 200ml = 10/L.
Many fragments of weeds and algae. 8-10 Daphnia per 200 ml = 45/L (quite healthy).
Zero Daphnia seen - wind NW 10 MPH
Site depth of 38 feet.  100% cloud cover- rain- nw wind 5-10 mph.  Hydrolab quanta used for profile.  200 mls filtered for chlorophyll.
Bryce Szymanski assisted in data collection
lots of algea and torn reed stalks- windy this week. (3.3 Daphnia/L)
clear- sunny- cool.  heavy algae bloom- no wind surface is like glass.
Special sample due to abundant algae reported by volunteer...
Cloudy- Indy Temps in the high 40's
South wind at 5 MPH. Few clouds. Air temp. 60.3.
cloudy. lots of algae. No daphnia- just algae in the water.
very windy- no daphnia- just algae NW wind 10-15 MPH. Cloudy- algae in water.
Depth finder on DO meter did not work - unable to find deep hole
SW wind 15-25 MPH. Waves 1 to 2 feet. Cloudy. Anchor was imbedded in muck but boat drifted some anyway.
Ph Probe broken - no Ph taken
Light west wind- Partly cloudy- Temp. 82

Starting to see bits of algae in the water
